**M39 — under-normalized accumulation on skipped channels:** when a channel is skipped (`w ≤ 0.001` or `layer ≥ layer_count`), albedo/roughness keep the deficit (only `detail_normal` is renormalized) — fragments darken slightly wherever an id is out of range (i.e., precisely in Bug 42's failure mode, making it *harder* to spot). After the fixed-slot refactor, divide albedo/roughness/metallic by the accumulated weight too.

## What's verified good — the Part 19 checklist, mostly passed

This shader clears most of the audit: triplanar weights are `pow(abs(n), sharpness)`, normalized, with a degenerate-normal fallback; projection axis pairs are correct (`zy`/`xz`/`xy`); texture scale is applied exactly once (global ÷ per-layer meters-per-repeat, guarded against 0); and — important given Bug 8's seams — UVs derive from **world position** with translation-only chunk transforms, so texturing is continuous across chunk boundaries by construction. The normal handling is genuinely careful: correct UDN-style per-projection swizzles for each axis pair, **including the negative-axis sign flip** the doc lists as a commonly-missed case; decode convention matches `normal.rs`'s OpenGL-style green channel; blended normal renormalized. Material transitions are computed per-fragment, not per-vertex (doc's interpolation-artifact check). `bake.rs` uploads sane real settings (sharpness 4.0, scale 1.0, averaged normal strength), and the all-zeros `Default` hazard is unreachable because the fallback material short-circuits on `debug_mode = 2` before any zero-scale sampling. At 256 m world scale there's no f32-precision/origin-rebase concern (revisit if the archipelago target arrives). Fix Bugs 41/44/45 and this becomes a solid terrain shader.